Croatian stocks mixed , prices to stagnate . Croatian stocks were mixed in active trade on Tuesday but market participants predicted a period of stagnation for most issues as large investors stayed away from the market . Traders said weaker demand was due to a constellation of factors , among other the latest unrest in the neigbouring Bosnia where one man was killed and some 20 wounded in an incident in the southern town of Mostar three weeks ago . " Investors in all new countries are more concerned with political risks than with prospects of firms they are interested in , " said Marko Nikolac of Metroholding brokerage . He said the fact that Croatia is a month away from regional elections could also contribute to poorer trading . Five of 14 active issues rose , two were flat and seven fell . Share volume rose to 10 , 016 from 7 , 114 shares , turnover was also slightly higher at 4 . 8 million kuna . Nikolac singled out Dalmatinska and Varazdinska Banka as possible future gainers " amid rumours the two are soon to be fully - listed ( on the Zagreb Stock Exchange ) " . Dalmatinska lost 15 kuna to 485 on volume of 895 units . Varazdinska was not active . Electrical manufacturer Koncar stole the spotlight on Tuesday , rising 1 , 090 kuna to 1 , 460 , with only 78 shares sold in a first and only transaction since last November . Traders said the stock could grow , boosted by recent news about its flotation abroad . " But it remains yet to be seen how Koncar would behave . At the moment there are no selling nor buying orders for its shares , " Nikolac said . Fully - listed Zagrebacka Banka inched down six kuna to 1 , 714 , selling 402 shares . Drugs firm Pliva traded flat at 460 kuna but was among most active issues with 1 , 041 units sold . Traders said the two were affected by their London prices which dipped due to a stronger dollar . Biggest decliner hotelier Istraturist lost 15 kuna to 205 on volume of 38 shares . Jadranturist lost four kuna to 310 and Laguna was flat at 1 , 400 kuna . Two other hoteliers , Riviera and Suncani Hvar both added one kuna to 180 and 68 , respectively . Most active stock food processor Podravka sold 3 , 889 shares , inching down five kuna to 305 . Chocolate maker Kras gained 40 kuna to 515 , trading 1 , 095 shares . The second tranche of public debt refinancing bonds traded at 12 . 14 percent above face value , up from 10 percent in February . The total turnover for the first and second trancheS was 437 . 7 million kuna . 
